<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Apparently you people have little to no clue what it involves to make a MMORPG the size of Everquest, or the size of any MMORPG for that matter.<P>The task is almost overwhelming and much less profitable than you would think.  Consider these basic business costs.  The bandwidth costs to support EQ probably range in the $250,000 to $600,000 per month range.  The cost to set up a single server bank can range anywhere from $250,000 to $1,000,000 .  Let's say they make around $50,000 per year each (I am trying to average on this, because I know they don't all make that, but some make much more), you are looking at a little over $4000 per month or $200,000 in just Salaries.  Oh, I forgot the GMs and support people, I will say there are around 50 GMs (I may be way off on that, I am just counting servers X 2, because there are people that answer emails as well that you never see on the servers) and we will say they make $18000 to $25000 per year, that averages to about $1900 a month x 50, or $95,000 per month.  Then you have to look at benefits, so you can almost double that.  Then, you have to look at advertising costs.  The price to advertise in a gaming magazine can range from $1500 to $50,000 depending on the ad, they definitely do more than one ad a month<P>Bandwidth $250,000 - $600,000<BR>Server Banks $250,000 - $1,000,000<BR>Programmers / Devs $200,000<BR>Support $95,000<BR>Advertising $15,000 - $500,000 (including salaries for marketing)<BR>Rent / Controllables $20,000 (average)<BR>E3 - Booth Cost alone is about $1,000,000 (Design, rent, marketing materials, parties for contacts, etc.) - And that is to get the name out there.<BR>GDC - Booth Cost is about $500,000 (Design, rent, rinse repeat etc.) - Although I can't figure out why.<BR>ECTS - Booth Cost is probably somewhere around GDC price or maybe lower.<BR>There are many more costs I haven't named, but those are the more obvious.<P>Some of these costs are shown conservative and some are probably a little more, but honestly they are not much more.  I am not saying I like the idea of paying more for EQ, but I can definitely undestand the idea.  Dark Age of Camelot charges $12.95, Anarchy Online charges $12.95, they both set the bar for this price and I think it is a good idea.  I can almost guarantee the next bar to be $19.95, and the sorry souls that frequent this world (including me), will pay that.<P>EQ has added several free zones since the game began and works continuously to improve service and the game.  Just because your Monk didn't get new gloves doesn't mean they aren't working their butts off.  While you guys complain, I can bet that 95% of you are not in the gaming industry and have no clue what goes into 75% of game creation and the service surrounding that game creation.  And I don't count game reviewers as being gaming industry, they are in the magazine industry.<P>Am I happy with everything that has happened with EQ in the time I have played (Beta 3), no I am not.  I wish Enchanters were actually what the original manual said they would be, but they aren't.  But, I know damn well they are trying their hardest to keep customers, and they know competition is only another server away.<P>Sony and Verant, good move on the $12.95 and I hope we see the results!<P>Just my .02
</FONT>
